## 4. The Database Layer

Instead of using SQLite or MongoDB (which often cause installation issues on Windows/Node 24 systems), AdvScribbl uses a custom JavaScript mock database system in [db.js](file:///c:/Users/PK'S/OneDrive/Desktop/AdvScribblw-with-backend-main/backend/db.js).

### JSON Flat-Files
The data is persisted in two files:
*   [users_db.json](file:///c:/Users/PK'S/OneDrive/Desktop/AdvScribblw-with-backend-main/backend/data/users_db.json): Stores user records, password hashes, registration times, and premium fields.
*   `payments_db.json`: Logs order receipts, amount counts, and processing statuses.

### Synchronous & Atomic Transactions
```javascript
function readJSON(file) {
  if (!fs.existsSync(file)) return [];
  try { return JSON.parse(fs.readFileSync(file, 'utf8')); }
  catch (err) { return []; }
}
function writeJSON(file, data) {
  fs.writeFileSync(file, JSON.stringify(data, null, 2), 'utf8');
}
```
All database queries (`get` and `run`) operate **synchronously**. Since Node.js is single-threaded, running database reads and writes synchronously ensures that operations are executed atomically. This prevents race conditions where concurrent signups could overwrite each other on disk.

